      "content": "Research has shown that African Americans tend to have a higher proportion of fast-twitch muscle fibers (approximately 60-70%), which are better suited for explosive, power-based activities such as sprinting and jumping. In contrast, European Americans tend to have a higher proportion of slow-twitch muscle fibers (approximately 40-50%), which are better suited for endurance activities such as distance running and cycling. Additionally, studies have found that East Asian populations tend to have a higher percentage of type I muscle fibers, which are even more specialized for endurance activities. However, it's essential to note that these differences are relatively small and influenced by a complex interplay of genetic and environmental factors.",
